                     <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2414" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I discharged the prisoner for another offence; I did not speak to him on this subject.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-263-person2415">
                  JAMES 
                  HAWTHORN
               <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2415" type="surname" value="HAWTHORN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2415" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2415" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was applied to, and took the prisoner; he said the reason he kept the loaves, was his master not paying his wages.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I deny it; I met a man the night before, who said Mr. Thurgood had been accusing me of stealing eight loaves - I went home, and asked Mr. Thurgood if he had said such a thing; he said No: I went on the 8th of September to the shop, and was to take sixteen loaves, but we had not much bread, and I took but twelve, and booked twelve in the shop.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-263-person2416">
                  JABEZ 
                  THURGOOD
               <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2416" type="surname" value="THURGOOD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2416" type="given" value="JABEZ"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-263-person2416" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have known him eight or nine years - he bore a good character; I paid him all up on the Tuesday evening - he did come back, and said he understood he was accused of robbing me.</p>
